{"key":"processedPost-5090104","value":{"id":5090104,"first":5090071,"last":5090418,"when":1135198520,"utime":"12/21/05 10:55 PM","content":"No.<br />Two reasons.  One, mag is not good for mushrooms.  Many growers have reported problems with fruiting whenever high levels of magnesium are present.<br /><br />Secondly, dolomitic lime is very slow to break down and is intended for outdoor flowerbeds and lawns where it has all season to work.  For balancing a casing, we need a very fast acting lime that goes to work right away since the average life of a casing is measured in weeks, not months or years.  I recommend hydrated lime.  You can get it online at <a href=\"http://www.doitbest.com\" target=\"_blank\">www.doitbest.com</a> if it's not available in your area. When you get to their site, just do a search for 'hydrated lime'.  I use the 'good earth' brand.<br />RR","title":"Re: Can you use Calcium-magnesium carbonate?","forum":"Mushroom Cultivation"}}